I think it is impossible to say
because there are so many choices for 4th and 5th moves
these kind of moves always are interesting :)
but, especially in an opening, whose theory is well known,
a good player can calculate possible variants, and see, which stone might help either color
in this way, there is no need to study the openings? right?
but it is big help I think
if the 1st player puts a sure win opening
it would be tempting to say, that of course there is still advantage
no sure win but still advantage
because the 1st player gets to choose the color also after next moves
if RT opened this ,maby he can win
in many cases, it is possible to change the position with 2 moves to be a variant of another opening
which might be weak for the starting player
in this case, the advantage turns to disadvantage even
so there are no 4. and 5. moves which gives balanced pattern?
and that is the point of this rule
to start the game as a balanced position
but, anyone who has played Sakata
knows, that finding this kind of 4th and 5th is hard
as was seen in Online Tournament a week ago
yes. So need lots of study
yes, that's why i said "well prepared"
the importance of focus in start of game is bigger than with RIF rules, I think
if somebody study enough kinds 4&5 about this opening,he will better than others
if i play against ando does not matter the rule...
but there can always be some pair of moves, that you haven't studied
so preparation with Sakata is much harder

the idea behind new rules is, that former theory most be included
but the best rule is the one, that supports old theory
and gives a chance for new players to play even with no knowledge of theories
this much is said, and time will tell, what kind of rules we will have
